"Ahas R., Aasa A.","The effects of climate change on the phenology of selected Estonian plant, bird and fish populations",2006,"International Journal of Biometeorology","51","1",,"17","26",,,10.1007/s00484-006-0041-z,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33748345838&partnerID=40&md5=1bff0f37d161624062307e780dcbf799","Institute of Geography, University of Tartu, 46 Vanemuise St., Tartu 51014, Estonia","Ahas, R., Institute of Geography, University of Tartu, 46 Vanemuise St., Tartu 51014, Estonia; Aasa, A., Institute of Geography, University of Tartu, 46 Vanemuise St., Tartu 51014, Estonia","This paper summarises the trends of 943 phenological time-series of plants, fishes and birds gathered from 1948 to 1999 in Estonia. More than 80% of the studied phenological phases have advanced during springtime, whereas changes are smaller during summer and autumn. Significant values of plant and bird phases have advanced 5-20 days, and fish phases have advanced 10-30 days in the spring period. Estonia's average air temperature has become significantly warmer in spring, while at the same time a slight decrease in air temperature has been detected in autumn. The growing season has become significantly longer in the maritime climate area of Western Estonia. The investigated phenological and climate trends are related primarily to changes in the North Atlantic Oscillation Index (NAOI) during the winter months. Although the impact of the winter NAOI on the phases decreases towards summer, the trends of the investigated phases remain high. The trends of phenophases at the end of spring and the beginning of summer may be caused by the temperature inertia of the changing winter, changes in the radiation balance or the direct consequences of human impacts such as land use, heat islands or air pollution.","Climate change; Estonia; Global warming; Phenological trends; Phenology","animal; article; bird; climate; ecosystem; Estonia; fish; flying; greenhouse effect; growth, development and aging; meteorological phenomena; physiology; plant; season; Animals; Birds; Climate; Ecosystem; Estonia; Fishes; Flight, Animal; Greenhouse Effect; Meteorological Concepts; Meteorological Factors; Plants; Seasons; Aves; Pisces",,,,,,"Aasa, A., Eesti agrofenoloogiline kalender (2001) Eesti Looduse Kalender, pp. 139-163. , Ahas R (ed). TÜ geograafia instituut, Tartu; Aasa, A., (2005) Changes in Phonological Time Series in Estonia and Central and Eastern Europe 1951-1998, Relationships with Air Temperature and Atmospheric Circulation, , PhD Thesis, University of Tartu; Aasa, A., Jaagus, J., Ahas, R., Sepp, M., The influence of atmospheric circulation on plant phenological phases in central and eastern Europe (2004) Int J Climatol, 24, pp. 1551-1564; Ahas, R., Long-term phyto-, ornitho- and ichtyophenological time-series analysis in Estonia (1999) Int J Biometeorol, 42, pp. 119-124; Ahas, R., Eesti taimefenoloogiline kalender (2001) Eesti Looduse Kalender, pp. 82-110. , Ahas R (ed). TÜ Geograafia Instituut, Tartu; Ahas, R., Aasa, A., Impact of landscape features on spring phenological phases of maple and bird cherry in Estonia (2001) Landsc Ecol, 16, pp. 437-451; Ahas, R., Aasa, A., Developing comparative phenological calendars (2003) Phenology: An Integrative Environmental Science, , Schwartz MD (ed). Kluwer, Dordrecht; Ahas, R., Jaagus, J., Aasa, A., The phenological calendar of Estonia and its correlation with mean air temperature (2000) Int J Biometeorol, 44, pp. 159-166; Ahas, R., Aasa, A., Menzel, A., Fedotova, V.G., Scheifinger, H., Changes in European spring phenology (2002) Int J Climatol, 22, pp. 1727-1738; Beaubien, E.G., Freeland, H.J., Spring phenology trends in Alberta, Canada: Links to ocean temperature (2000) Int J Biometeorol, 44, pp. 53-59; Chen, X., Tan, Z., Schwartz, M.D., Xu, C., Determining the growing season of land vegetation on the basis of plant phenology and satellite data in Northern China (2000) Int J Biometeorol, 44, pp. 97-101;